  "signature": "ed25519:b1d4e7f2a09c3e56f8b2d1a4c7e09f3b5d8a2c6e1f4b7d0a3c9e2f5b8d1a4c7",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Software used for CFD simulation must be under documented version control, with regression test suite coverage confirmed for hemolysis-relevant solver modules. Required at Gradation 3 for MRL 5.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2021 R2 is used under ISO 9001-compliant quality management. Version control is documented in the project configuration management plan. Regression tests covering turbulence model integration, species transport, and UDF hemolysis damage accumulation routines were executed and passed prior to simulation campaign. SQA level assessed as meeting Gradation 3 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver must be verified against at least two published benchmark problems with known analytical or high-fidelity reference solutions relevant to the flow physics (rotating machinery, non-Newtonian viscosity, or hemolysis transport).",
      "rationale": "Code verification performed against the Taylor-Couette analytical solution for laminar Couette flow and the Ghia et al. lid-driven cavity benchmark at Re 1000. Both benchmarks show L2 errors below 0.5% on the production mesh topology. A third verification against the Gijsen non-Newtonian pipe-flow analytical solution confirms correct Carreau-Yasuda viscosity implementation. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "For MRL 5, discretization error must be quantified via a formal GCI study across at least three systematically refined meshes, with GCI < 5% on hemolysis index QoI and Richardson extrapolation applied. Achieved level must reach Gradation 4.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted with refinement ratio r = 1.3 applied uniformly. GCI values for pressure rise and bulk velocity are below 3%, satisfying Gradation 3 criteria for those quantities. However, the hemolysis index QoI — the primary decision-relevant output — exhibits GCI of 18.7% between the medium and fine meshes, and Richardson extrapolation reveals the solution has not entered the asymptotic convergence regime on the fine mesh. This shortfall limits the achievable discretization error gradation to 2 for the hemolysis QoI specifically. The gap between required Gradation 4 and achieved Gradation 2 represents an unresolved credibility deficit for the primary quantity of interest. A finer mesh study was scoped but deferred due to HPC resource constraints; the deficit is acknowledged in the uncertainty budget but no compensating evidence was provided."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation must be documented with traceability to calibrated measurement systems. Operating conditions must span the COU envelope (5 flow-speed combinations).",
      "rationale": "FDA flow-loop experiments were conducted at five operating points spanning 3–6 L/min and 2400–3600 RPM. All flow meters and pressure transducers are NIST-traceable with calibration certificates dated within 12 months of test execution. Temperature was maintained at 37 ± 0.5°C using a thermostatically controlled bath. Bovine blood hematocrit was verified at 30 ± 1% for each test run. Test condition documentation satisfies Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation outputs must be compared to experimental measurements using a quantitative metric (e.g., E%, NRMSE) with uncertainty bands from both simulation and experiment explicitly reported.",
      "rationale": "Hemolysis index predictions are compared to FDA flow-loop measurements using normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) as the primary metric. Mean absolute percentage error across five operating points is 11.4%, within the acceptance threshold of 15% established in the validation plan. Experimental measurement uncertainty (±8% at 95% confidence) and simulation prediction interval from Monte Carlo UQ (±12% at 95%) are both reported. Comparison satisfies Gradation 3 requirements for output comparison."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoIs used in validation must be directly relevant to the clinical decision quantity (absolute hemolysis index). Surrogate or indirect QoIs must be justified.",
      "rationale": "The primary validation QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH), which is the regulatory-accepted metric for absolute hemolysis in VAD assessments per FDA guidance. Secondary QoIs include pressure rise across the pump and volumetric flow rate, both of which are direct inputs to the hemolysis damage accumulation model. No surrogate QoIs are used without justification. Relevance assessed at Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments must use the same pump geometry, blood analog properties, and operating envelope as the COU. Deviations must be documented and their impact on credibility assessed.",
      "rationale": "Validation activities use the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry identical to the COU device. Bovine blood with matched hematocrit is used as the working fluid; the Carreau-Yasuda viscosity parameters for bovine blood at 37°C are within 5% of human blood parameters at the relevant shear rates. Operating conditions span the full COU envelope. One deviation is noted: validation experiments were conducted at atmospheric outlet pressure whereas COU involves physiological afterload; sensitivity analysis shows less than 3% effect on NIH predictions. Relevance assessed at Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated for all simulations. Residual targets and mass/momentum imbalance criteria must be defined and met.",
      "rationale": "All steady-state simulations are converged to scaled residuals below 1×10⁻⁵ for continuity, momentum, and species transport equations. Global mass imbalance is below 0.01% for all five operating points. Convergence monitoring plots are archived in the simulation record. For the transient UQ ensemble runs, time-averaged quantities are confirmed stationary over the final two impeller revolutions. Solver error assessed at Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Evidence that the simulation was set up and executed by qualified personnel following documented procedures, with independent review of boundary conditions and model parameters.",
      "rationale": "Simulation setup was performed by a PhD-level CFD engineer with 8 years of cardiovascular device simulation experience. Boundary conditions and turbulence model selections were independently reviewed by a second senior engineer prior to production runs. A simulation setup checklist aligned with FDA computational fluid dynamics guidance was completed and archived. Use error assessed at Gradation 2, meeting the required level for this factor."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The turbulence model, constitutive relations, and hemolysis damage accumulation model must be justified for the flow regime and validated against relevant benchmark data.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-ω turbulence model is selected based on its established performance for rotating machinery flows at transitional Reynolds numbers (Re ~ 10³–10⁴). The Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power-law model is used with Lagrangian particle tracking for damage accumulation; this model form is consistent with FDA-cited literature for centrifugal pump hemolysis prediction. Model form justification document references five peer-reviewed publications supporting the selected constitutive relations. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model input parameters must be documented with sources, nominal values, and uncertainty ranges. Monte Carlo sampling distributions must be justified.",
      "rationale": "Forty-one model input parameters are catalogued in the uncertainty quantification plan. Key uncertain inputs include Carreau-Yasuda viscosity coefficients (literature-derived with ±10% coefficient of variation), hemolysis model exponents α and β (literature range applied as uniform distributions), and impeller tip clearance (manufacturing tolerance ±0.05 mm). Monte Carlo sampling uses Latin hypercube sampling with 500 samples; convergence of output statistics is confirmed at N=400. Input documentation satisfies Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental samples (blood batches, pump units) must be characterized and their representativeness of the COU population assessed.",
      "rationale": "Three bovine blood batches were used across the validation campaign. Each batch was characterized for hematocrit, osmolality, and baseline plasma free hemoglobin prior to testing. Two pump units from the same manufacturing lot were tested; dimensional inspection confirmed both units are within design tolerances. Sample representativeness is assessed as adequate for Gradation 2, which is the required level for this factor at MRL 5 given the availability of only bovine (not human) blood."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The input parameters used in validation simulations must be shown to be equivalent (or bounding) relative to those used in COU simulations. Differences must be quantified and their effect on QoI assessed.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency matrix comparing validation simulation inputs to COU simulation inputs is documented for all 41 uncertain parameters. The most significant difference is the use of bovine blood viscosity parameters in validation versus human blood parameters in COU; sensitivity analysis shows this introduces a maximum 4.2% difference in predicted NIH, which is within the stated validation uncertainty band. All geometric inputs are identical between validation and COU simulations. Equivalency assessed at Gradation 3."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou2-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-lead",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team reviewed all thirteen credibility factors. Twelve of thirteen factors achieve their required levels, and the overall V&V campaign is judged to be thorough and well-documented. The Discretization error factor GCI shortfall for the hemolysis QoI is noted in the uncertainty budget; the team concludes that the Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification — which propagates input parameter uncertainty through the model — provides compensating coverage for the unresolved discretization uncertainty, and that the 11.4% mean absolute error in output comparison is within the pre-specified acceptance threshold. On the basis of this holistic assessment, the team declares a Medium assurance level and an Accepted decision, concluding that the CFD model provides adequate credibility for its intended use in the VAD hemolysis regulatory submission.",
